When Octavius had teleneu the consulship, he ascended to the Capitol to make the usual vows and sacrifices3 paid Caesar's bequests to the people; thanked the senate for releasing him from the restrictiou of the ‘Leges Annales' and procured the enactment of a ‘Iex Curiata'' to sanction his adoption. Other laws of importance followed ; one remowing the outlawry of Dolabella, and another* directing that an enquiry should be made about the murder of Caesar, and fixing a punishment for the principals and accomplices in it. Under this law, the conspirators and others who had merely sympathised with them were condemned in their absence to exile and confiscation, which of course implied the loss of commands and provinces ⁸.
